  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Unapproved building works are one of the more common complications that come up during property sales in Brisbane's inner east. Older Queenslander homes in particular frequently have additions, extensions, or structural changes made over the decades by previous owners who did not always obtain the required approvals. When a buyer's solicitor or building inspector identifies unapproved works, the transaction can stall while the parties work out who is responsible for the cost and process of regularising the works. Knowing your property's approval status before you list puts you in control of how this issue is handled rather than reacting to it under contract.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What building approval means and when it is required</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, building approval refers to the approval required under the Building Act 1975 for most building work. It is the confirmation that the proposed or completed works comply with the Building Code of Australia and relevant Queensland standards. Building approval is required for most structural work: new dwellings, extensions, additions, carports, garages, decks, pools, and any work that affects the structural integrity or use of the building.</p>

      <p>There is an important distinction between development approval and building approval. Development approval (sometimes called planning approval or a material change of use) is a planning permit issued under the Planning Act 2016. It governs whether the proposed use or development is permissible under local government planning rules, including zoning, setbacks, height, and site coverage. Building approval is separate and deals with how the structure is built relative to the building code. Some projects require both. A two-storey extension, for example, may require both development approval from Brisbane City Council and building approval from either council or a private certifier. A new deck in a standard residential backyard generally requires building approval only, not development approval, provided it is within the setback rules.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to check whether your works have approval</h2>
      <p>The most reliable way to check approval status is through Brisbane City Council's online property records. The Council's PD Online system allows you to search by address and view lodged applications, approvals, and certificates associated with the property. You can see whether building applications were lodged for specific works and whether they were approved and certified. Older approvals may not be digitised, but Council can assist with historical record searches through a formal request.</p>

      <p>Your conveyancer or solicitor can also conduct a property search that includes building and planning records. This is a standard part of the due diligence process and is routinely done by buyers' solicitors. As a seller, conducting this search yourself before listing means you are aware of any gaps before a buyer's representative finds them for you. There is a significant difference between disclosing a known issue proactively and having it surface mid-contract during buyer due diligence.</p>

      <p>A building and pest inspector engaged by a buyer will typically note any structures that appear to have been built without approval, based on their visual inspection. They will not have access to council records, but they will flag structures whose age, construction quality, or configuration suggests they may not have been through a formal approval process. This flag then prompts the buyer's solicitor to investigate further.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Retrospective approval in Brisbane</h2>
      <p>If works on your property were completed without approval, retrospective approval (sometimes called building approval for existing work) is possible in Queensland. The process involves engaging a private building certifier who will assess the existing works against the standards that applied at the time the work was done, or in some cases current standards. The certifier inspects the works, reviews available documentation, and determines whether an approval can be issued.</p>

      <p>For older works that predate current codes, the assessment may be done against the standards applicable when the work was originally carried out. This is relevant for period homes where older construction methods were used. The process is not always quick or cheap, but it is generally preferable to leaving unapproved works undisclosed and having them surface during a sale. A property where known unapproved works have been retrospectively approved is in a materially better position than one where they have not.</p>

      <p>In some cases, retrospective approval is not possible because the works do not comply with the relevant standards and cannot be made to comply without significant modification. In those situations, the vendor needs to either remedy the works to a compliant standard or disclose the issue to buyers clearly and price accordingly. An unapproved structure that cannot be approved is not necessarily a deal-breaker, but it is a material fact that must be disclosed and that buyers will factor into their offer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a private certifier does and when sellers use one</h2>
      <p>A private building certifier is a licensed professional who has authority under Queensland law to assess building work against the building code and issue approvals and certificates. They operate as an alternative to council approval for most residential building work. Private certifiers are commonly used because they tend to offer faster turnaround times than council, can be engaged directly by the building owner, and have the authority to certify both new work and existing work.</p>

      <p>Sellers use private certifiers when they need to address an approval gap before listing, or during a sale when a buyer makes the resolution of an unapproved structure a condition of contract. The certifier inspects the works, assesses their compliance, and if satisfied issues the relevant certificate. The cost varies depending on the complexity and scope of the works, and sellers should get a quote before instructing the certifier, as the fees can be more than expected for complex structures or unusual situations.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Impact on your sale timeline and price</h2>
      <p>If unapproved works are identified after a contract is signed, the practical impact depends on how the contract addresses the issue. In Queensland, standard contracts do not automatically allow a buyer to rescind solely because of unapproved structures, but unapproved works can become a leverage point in renegotiation and can trigger delays while the parties sort out who is responsible. Some buyers will request a price reduction to account for the cost of retrospective approval. Others will ask the vendor to rectify the issue prior to settlement. Some will seek to terminate if the unapproved works are significant enough to constitute a breach of the contract terms or if the works cannot be approved.</p>

      <p>From a practical perspective, addressing known unapproved works before going to market is almost always better than allowing them to surface during the transaction. The cost of engaging a private certifier to regularise an existing deck, carport, or addition is typically modest compared to the risk of a renegotiation or delayed settlement under contract. It also removes a point of uncertainty that buyers and their agents will factor into their offer, consciously or not, when deciding what to pay for a property that they know has compliance issues outstanding.</p>

      <p>Your solicitor or conveyancer should be your first call if you have concerns about the approval status of works on your property. They can advise on your disclosure obligations and help you understand the specific risk profile for your situation before you list.</p>

